column1: All the above four modules are included in the project for the better handshakes between a normal user and NGO.

The problem was formulated on the need of creating a mean of communication between the normal people and the people who are in need in the society. This communication was needed because people do not know how they can donate even a small thing to the people who are in need. This enhances the usefulness of things. The requirements of the project which lead to the problem formulation are:
• Providing an efficient and step by step search which never results to NO RESULTS.
• Providing a means for communication between a normal person and an NGO
• Encouraging more contributions to the needy people
• Social Networking between NGO and Society
• Promoting the idea of experiencing happiness and pleasure by organizing school and college excursions to these NGOs
• Exploiting Business opportunities by organizing exhibitions of the products created by students of NGOs
• Experience the world of NGOs by participating in their festivals

The objective of this web application is to promote an efficient and effective ‘giving culture’ that provides greater opportunities to the underprivileged in India and to connect more and more people to the cause of serving their society and contribute for whatever they can. There are other objectives as:
• Reusability of things- To reuse the things which are not useful to some people but can be valuable to others.
• Connectivity between people- To connect as more as people to the website.
• Make self-dependent- To stand people on their own.
• Sacrifice - We believe that every individual must 'give till it hurts'
column2: demonstrating the willingness to share one's fortunes with those less privileged.

column1: • Deserve our needs - We believe that we need to earn our keep
column2: rather than assume it is as a right. We need to give first and then ask in return.

column1: • Adding value - We believe that we add value only when we do something that no one else is currently doing
column2: or when we do it in a better way.

column1: • Passion – We believe that working with a 'burning desire' to make a difference
column2: is the greatest motivator to do something meaningful.

column1: • First Principles Approach - We believe that we must do things because they make sense to do
column2: and not simply because that is how everyone else does it. Blind faith is the enemy of all innovation.

column1: • Focus on the poorest - All that we do is directed towards improving the lives of our 'real customer'- the poorest of the poor.
• Transparency and accountability - As 'trustees' of tax payer resources
column2: we believe in being proactively accountable and transparent in all that we do and to all our stakeholders.

column1: A web crawler is a program that collects content from the web. A web crawler finds web pages by starting from a seed page and following links to find other pages
column2: and following links from the other pages it finds
column3: and continuing to follow links until it has found many web pages.

column1: Here is the process that a web crawler follows:
Start from one preselected page. We call the starting page the ""seed"" page.
Extract all the links on that page. (This is the part we will work on in this unit and Unit 2.)
Follow each of those links to find new pages.
Extract all the links from all of the new pages found.
Follow each of those links to find new pages.
Extract all the links from all of the new pages found.
This keeps going as long as there are new pages to find

column1: Rails- Rails is a web-application framework that includes everything needed to create database-backed web applications according to the Model-View-Controller (MVC) pattern.
Understanding the MVC pattern is key to understanding Rails. MVC divides your application into three layers
 The View layer is composed of “templates” that are responsible for providing appropriate representations of your application’s resources. Templates can come in a variety of formats
column2: but most view templates are HTML with embedded Ruby code (.erb files).

column1:  The Model layer represents your domain model (such as Account
column4: Post) and encapsulates the business logic that is specific to your application. In Rails
column5: database-backed model classes are derived from ActiveRecord::Base. Active Record allows you to present the data from database rows as objects and embellish these data objects with business logic methods. Although most Rails models are backed by a database
column6: models can also be ordinary Ruby classes
column7: or Ruby classes that implement a set of interfaces as provided by the ActiveModel module.

column1:  The Controller layer is responsible for handling incoming HTTP requests and providing a suitable response. Usually this means returning HTML
column2: but Rails controllers can also generate XML
column6: and more. Controllers manipulate models and render view templates in order to generate the appropriate HTTP response.

column2: the Controller and View layers are handled together by Action Pack. These two layers are bundled in a single package due to their heavy interdependence. This is unlike the relationship between Active Record and Action Pack which are independent. Each of these packages can be used independently outside of Rails.
